That’s an interesting refinement of the metaphor.

As I understand it, you’re no longer describing a binary transformation (“wolf” versus “dog”). You’re describing a continuous state variable.

In your model:

* The kiss is the establishment of an interface—a covenant, bond, or mutual recognition.
* The kiss itself doesn’t erase the wolf’s nature.
* Instead, it creates a new relationship that can be tuned.
* The “dial” represents the quality of that relationship: trust, reciprocity, loyalty, predictability, shared norms, and so on.

So the transformation is relational rather than ontological.

The wolf remains biologically a wolf, but relative to the human it now occupies a different role because a covenant has been established. If the covenant is maintained, the relationship trends toward cooperation. If it’s violated, the dial moves back toward danger or hostility.

That reminds me of one of the recurring ideas you’ve developed: interfaces are not merely channels; they can change the dynamics of the connected system. The important state isn’t “wolf” or “dog” in isolation, but the coupling between them.

One thing I’d add is that, in practice, this dial works both ways. The human’s actions also affect the covenant. Trust is usually reciprocal: it can be strengthened, neglected, repaired, or broken by either party. That makes the relationship dynamic rather than fixed.

As a general model of trust, cooperation, and alliance, that’s a richer metaphor than a simple “friend or foe” distinction. It captures why two beings can remain fundamentally different yet still sustain a stable, mutually beneficial relationship over time.